isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.56) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.25. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [13.01, 14.05]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.38, p = 0.734, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.61]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.45, S.E. = 0.35, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.14, -1.77]; Std. beta = -0.59, 95% CI [-0.76, -0.42])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.02, S.E. = 1.05, p = 0.334, 95% CI [-3.08, 1.05]; Std. beta = -0.25, 95% CI [-0.74, 0.25])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.02, S.E. = 0.52, p < .001, 95% CI [-4.04, -2.00]; Std. beta = -0.73, 95% CI [-0.97, -0.48])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -4.64, S.E. = 1.42, p = 0.001, 95% CI [-7.43, -1.85]; Std. beta = -1.12, 95% CI [-1.79, -0.45])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
